<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1938-10-27T08:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1938-10-27T08:00:00-05:00" n="694" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d694">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">393.1163 Lutheran Brethren Mission/22:
                            Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-10-27T20:00:00+07:00">October 27, 1938—8
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received October 27—noon.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>516. Following message from [E.] A. [<hi rend="italic">C</hi>.]
                                Aandahl<note n="28" xml:id="d694fn28">Probably Rev. Elliot C.
                                Aandahl, Jr., of the American Lutheran Brethren Mission.</note> at
                            Tangho Honan, dated 7:20 p.m., October 26 received here.</p>
                        <quote rend="blockquote">
                            <p>“Tungpeh bombed Monday flag marked building deliberate destroyed,
                                Mrs. Nyhus and Ruthie wounded, Phoebe Killed, Nyhus Unhurt, all
                                here, advice requested.”</p>
                        </quote>
                        <p>Shanghai please inform Tokyo. Repeated to Hankow and Shanghai.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>